			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Time.  Acomplishment.  Nearly all of the comments about needing "instant" travel are by people saying that travel is a waste of time, or that they could accomplish more fighting.
<br />

<br />
To these folks, consider something.  The journey is the fun, is it not?  Or do you simply want to be level 65 wth max AA?  You'll still be fighting monsters, its just a matter of which ones.
<br />

<br />
A long standing fact - fantasy role playing games do not end - there is no winner..  Noone cares if you can level faster or quicker...  This is not the one player PC game that you conquer and quit.  It is a living world to role play in - plain and simple.
<br />

<br />
The old game forced long travel.  My first trip across the commons, saw me being afraid to cross the toll gates there without talking to the guards.  I saw the landscape, the sky, I experienced the depth of the world of Norrath.  I experienced the pain of death, and a long CR.  Damn the people that invented no CR before level 10.  Now groups at level 11 have to deal with players that don't know how to find a corpse.
<br />

<br />
Fast travel, power levelling, twinking.... all ways to hasten the trip toward level 65.  WHY?  Don't people enjoy the game?  Don't like the graphics?  What is the point of being 65 anyway..  I've turned off regular experience completely on my level 61 (who has 180 days playing BTW, not 23 hours like the new level 61s).
<br />

<br />
Power levelling and twinking just makes sure we miss the various quests, mobs, NPCs and zones that our new characters might otherwise experience.  It makes sure that the new class we're playing isn't experienced at a pace where we can learn the subtleties of our class.  I was with a ranger the other day that didn't really know how to use track.  She was level 48.  She did know that she shouldn't figth without temperance, and that there was no sense fighting without someone to PL her...  Sad... truely sad...  Using guides for how to level fast makes sure we level quickly and fight in the crowded zones, rather than enjoy all that those levels have to offer.  I (Yalpeelor) fought in shadeweavers until 30.  Most people don't know mobs exist in shadeweavers past 16, they're too busy worrying about levelling real fast in god forsaken Paludal.
<br />

<br />
Frankly, I don't understand people that have to optimize everything in their lives.  Fast - fast - fast.  (I'd like to meet these people's wives though - sorry, hard to resist that jab) ;)
<br />

<br />

<br />
Sorry if I got a little to pointed with some of my points.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
